      <hedline>
        <hl1>Young Shoppers And American Values</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>L Stein letter on Lesley Jane Seymour's April 22 article on pre-teen shoppers</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Oh, please! I was so disgusted by the tone of ''Tweens 'R' Shoppers,'' by Lesley Jane Seymour (April 22), and put off by the photos of these spoiled, super-sophisticated sub-teens. If the majority of children in our country grow up with these values, we're in deep trouble.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Oh, please! I was so disgusted by the tone of ''Tweens 'R' Shoppers,'' by Lesley Jane Seymour (April 22), and put off by the photos of these spoiled, super-sophisticated sub-teens. If the majority of children in our country grow up with these values, we're in deep trouble.</p>
        <p>Only in certain affluent communities could a child walk around with a necklace like the one on Ms. Seymour's daughter, not to mention afford one, and think that looks normal. And the idea that shopping replaces a day spent together in cooking or other some other pursuit, and helps one learn to survive, is ridiculous.</p>
        <p>This article sends the wrong message. Parents really need to help their children grow in spirit, not in commercialism.</p>
        <p>L. Stein  Hauppauge</p>
      </block>
